Data Cleaning and Visualizations¶

Understanding the Datasets¶

Introductions to Datasets¶

likely contains information related to vehicles, such as their specifications, performance, or other details. To gain context, you may want to research the source of the data. If this is an older data set, you can search online for any updated versions or similar data sets that may contain newer or more relevant data. Websites like Kaggle or government databases (for vehicle statistics) can be good starting points for finding updated data.

Exploring the Fields (Columns) in the Dataset¶

You can use Python's libraries like pandas to load and explore the dataset. Begin by understanding the data types for each column, distinguishing between numerical, categorical, or text fields. Also, identify which columns represent dependent variables (target or output) and independent variables (features or input data).

Brief Description of the Datasets¶

The vehicles dataset contains information about various cars, including specifications like mileage, engine size, fuel type, price, and more. This dataset can be used to analyze trends in vehicle efficiency, price range, or the correlation between different factors.

Key Features of an Automotive Dataset¶

Make:¶

The manufacturer of the vehicle (e.g., Toyota, Ford, Honda).

Role:¶

Identifies the brand and can help in analyzing market trends based on brand popularity.

Model:¶

The specific name of the vehicle model (e.g., Camry, Mustang).

Role:¶

Useful for distinguishing between different vehicles produced by the same manufacturer.

Year:¶

The year the vehicle was manufactured.

Role:¶

Important for understanding trends over time, such as changes in pricing or fuel efficiency.

Price:¶

The selling price of the vehicle.

Role:¶

A crucial variable for market analysis and understanding consumer spending patterns.

Engine:¶

The engine of the vehicle's engine, often measured in liters (L).

Role:¶

Can be analyzed for its impact on fuel efficiency and performance.

Cylinders:¶

The number of cylinders in the engine.

Role:¶

Influences both power and fuel consumption; helps in classifying vehicle types.

Fuel (MPG):¶

The vehicle's miles per gallon (MPG) rating.

Role:¶

Indicates how fuel-efficient the vehicle is, a key factor for consumers.

Mileage:¶

The total distance the vehicle has traveled, often measured in miles.

Role:¶

Important for assessing vehicle wear and tear and resale value.

Transmission¶

Definition: The type of transmission (e.g., automatic, manual).

Role:¶

Affects driving experience and can influence consumer preference.

Body Style:¶

The physical configuration of the vehicle (e.g., coupe, hatchback).

Role:¶

Impacts consumer choice and marketing strategies.

Drivetrain:¶

The system that transmits power from the engine to the wheels (e.g., FWD, RWD, AWD).

Role:¶

Influences vehicle handling and performance characteristics.

Exterior Color:¶

The color of the vehicle's exterior.

Role:¶

Can be relevant for aesthetic preferences and market demand trends.

Interior Color:¶

The color of the vehicle's interior.

Role:¶

Similar to exterior color, impacts consumer preferences.

Trim:¶

The specific configuration or level of the vehicle, often indicating features and options included.

Role:¶

Helps in analyzing features and price variations within a model.

Safety Ratings:¶

Ratings given by safety organizations (e.g., NHTSA, IIHS).

Role:¶

Crucial for consumers when considering the safety of a vehicle.

List of Fields and Definitions¶

Make:¶

The manufacturer of the vehicle (e.g., Toyota, Ford).

Model:¶

The specific model of the vehicle (e.g., Corolla, Mustang).

Year:¶

The manufacturing year of the vehicle.

Fuel Type:¶

Type of fuel used (e.g., Gasoline, Diesel, Electric).

Engine Size (L):¶

The engine displacement in liters.

Horsepower:¶

The power output of the vehicle's engine.

MPG (City/Highway):¶

Miles per gallon for city and highway driving.

Price:¶

The selling price of the vehicle.

Transmission:¶

Type of transmission (Automatic, Manual).

Drivetrain:¶

The system that transmits power to the wheels (e.g., FWD, AWD).

Analysis of Existing Visualizations¶

Clarity of Representation¶

Examine if the visualization clearly presents the data and communicates the intended message. Is the audience able to quickly grasp the information, or is there confusion due to overcrowding or poor design

Relevance of the Chart Type to the Data¶

Determine whether the chart type appropriately fits the data being represented. For example, bar charts are ideal for categorical comparisons, while line charts are better for showing trends over time.

Ability to Reveal Insights or Patterns¶

Analyze how well the visualization helps uncover meaningful insights, trends, or outliers in the data.

Aesthetic Quality and Color Contrast¶

Evaluate whether the visual design enhances or detracts from the overall message. Aesthetics matter because they influence engagement, so a well-designed chart should be visually appealing without being distracting.

Clarity of Axes, Labels, Legends, and Titles¶

Ensure that all necessary labels, axes, legends, and titles are present and easily readable. This contributes to understanding the meaning of the visualization.

Visualization 1: Bar Chart Representing Vehicle price by Year¶

Chart Type¶

Keep the bar chart but consider adding data labels on top of each bar to show the exact price numbers. Alternatively, if comparing multiple categories (e.g., price by different regions), a stacked bar chart could add depth.

Color Scheme¶

Use a more distinct color palette with better contrast. Consider colorblind-friendly palettes such as ColorBrewer schemes.

Layout and Font Size¶

Increase the font size of the axis labels and title for better readability, especially if the chart is viewed on smaller screens.

Scaling¶

If there's a significant range difference in sales across years, adjusting the y-axis scale or using a logarithmic scale may help with better representation of smaller values.

Using a Color Palette¶

In [29]:
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(x='year', y='price', data=df, palette='Blues_d') 
plt.title('Vehicle price by Year', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('price', fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.show()

Visualization 2:Line Chart Showing Trends in Vehicle Prices Over Time¶

Chart Type¶

Consider switching to a facet grid (small multiples), where each line is plotted separately in smaller charts for better comparison. Alternatively, you can use a stacked area chart to show how the total price distribution changes over time, while still representing individual model trends.

Color Scheme¶

Use a gradient-based color scheme to differentiate between lines. Avoid using too many contrasting colors—select a lighter base and use intensity to represent growth or decline.

Layout¶

Spread out the data over a larger grid, allowing for more space between the lines, or use an interactive zoom feature to allow users to focus on specific years.

Scaling¶

If the data includes outliers, apply smoothing techniques (such as a moving average) to reduce noise and make the trends clearer.

In [32]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.lineplot(x='year', y='price', hue='model', data=df, palette='coolwarm', alpha=0.7)
df['price_smooth'] = df.groupby('model')['price'].transform(lambda x: x.rolling(3).mean())
sns.lineplot(x='year', y='price_smooth', hue='model', data=df, palette='coolwarm', linewidth=2)
plt.title('Trends in Vehicle Prices Over Time', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Price (in USD)', fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Visualization 3: Pie Chart Showing Vehicle Market Share by year¶

Chart Type¶

Replace the pie chart with a horizontal bar chart or stacked bar chart. These chart types are better suited for comparing values and highlighting differences year.

Color Scheme¶

Apply a sequential color scale where higher market share is represented with darker colors, making it easier to visually rank manufacturers.

Layout and Font Sizes¶

In a bar chart format, increase bar width and use large, clear font sizes for both labels and percentage values.

Interactivity¶

Add an interactive feature allowing users to click on a manufacturer to view detailed breakdowns of the models they offer, or their year-over-year price data.

In [39]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
market_share = df.groupby('year')['price'].sum().reset_index()
labels = market_share['year']
sizes = market_share['price']
#Create the pie chart
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.pie(sizes, labels=labels, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=140, colors=plt.cm.Paired.colors)
plt.title('Vehicle Market Share by year', fontsize=16)
plt.axis('equal')  
plt.show()

Visualization 4: Scatter Plot Showing Relationship Between Engine and Fuel¶

Chart Type¶

Consider adding a heatmap overlay to show density where data points overlap significantly. This will reveal the underlying distribution more clearly.

Color Scheme¶

Use a diverging color palette to represent different clusters of data points. Alternatively, use size or color to represent a third variable, such as vehicle type or price range.

Layout¶

Adjust the point size and transparency (alpha) to make overlapping points visible.

Axes¶

Label the axes more clearly and add gridlines to enhance readability and make it easier to compare values between different points.

In [50]:
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
df['engine'] = pd.to_numeric(df['engine'], errors='coerce')  
df['fuel'] = pd.to_numeric(df['fuel'], errors='coerce')
df.dropna(subset=['engine', 'fuel'], inplace=True)
if 'vehicle_type' in df.columns:
    hue_variable = 'vehicle_type'
else:
    hue_variable = None  
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
if hue_variable:
    sns.scatterplot(x='engine', y='fuel', data=df, hue=hue_variable, alpha=0.7, palette='viridis', s=100)
else:
    sns.scatterplot(x='engine', y='fuel', data=df, alpha=0.7, color='blue', s=100)
#Optionally add a regression line
sns.regplot(x='engine', y='fuel', data=df, scatter=False, color='red')
plt.title('Relationship Between Engine  and Fuel ', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Engine(L)', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Fuel (MPG)', fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True)
if hue_variable:
    plt.legend(title=hue_variable)
plt.show()

Improved Histogram for Vehicle Price Distribution¶

Chart Type¶

Keep the histogram but increase the number of bins to reveal finer details about the price distribution.

Color Scheme¶

Use a single-color gradient where darker shades represent higher frequencies to avoid confusion with multiple colors.

Scaling and Layout¶

Ensure the x-axis (prices) is evenly scaled to avoid distorting the view. Increase the histogram width to provide more space for individual bars.

Labels and Titles¶

Provide clearer axis labels (e.g., “Price Range (in USD)”) and a title that clarifies what the viewer should look for (e.g., “Distribution of Vehicle Prices Across All Models”).

Interactivity¶

Allow users to drag a selection over specific price ranges to filter and analyze vehicles within that range. This can be combined with dynamic price statistics (e.g., average price, median price) displayed as users interact with the chart.

In [58]:
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
df = pd.read_csv("C:\\Users\\rites\\OneDrive\\Desktop\\vehicles_dataset.csv")
df['price'] = pd.to_numeric(df['price'], errors='coerce')
df.dropna(subset=['price'], inplace=True)
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.histplot(df['price'], bins=30, kde=True, color='skyblue', alpha=0.7)
plt.title('Distribution of Vehicle Prices', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Price ($)', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Frequency', fontsize=12)
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.show()

Time Series Analysis: Line Chart¶

In [62]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sn
df['year'] = pd.to_numeric(df['year'], errors='coerce')
df['price'] = pd.to_numeric(df['price'], errors='coerce')
df.dropna(subset=['year', 'price'], inplace=True)
# Group by year to get average price
average_price = df.groupby('year')['price'].mean().reset_index()
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.lineplot(x='year', y='price', data=average_price, marker='o')
plt.title('Average Vehicle Price Over Time', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Average Price ($)', fontsize=12)
plt.axvspan(2008, 2009, color='red', alpha=0.2, label='Economic Downturn')
plt.legend()
plt.grid()
plt.show()

Insights from the New Visualizations¶

Vehicle Price Trends Over Time (Line Chart)¶

Insight:¶

The line chart clearly indicates an upward trend in vehicle prices over the years, suggesting increasing demand or inflation in the automotive market.

Interpretation:¶

Significant spikes in prices might correlate with specific economic events (e.g., tax incentives for electric vehicles) or shifts in consumer preferences. This suggests potential areas for further investigation or strategic marketing efforts.

Market Share by model and year (Pie Chart)¶

insight:¶

The pie chart highlights the distribution of market share among various vehicle model, revealing that a few model dominate the market.

Interpretation:¶

This concentration suggests opportunities for smaller model to capture niche markets or innovate in areas where larger companies are lacking. Understanding consumer preferences in this context can inform strategic decisions for new entrants or existing players.

Relationship Between Engine and Fuel (Scatter Plot)¶

Insight:¶

The scatter plot demonstrates a negative correlation between engine size and fuel efficiency, with most fuel-efficient vehicles having smaller engines.

Interpretation:¶

This trend underscores the growing consumer demand for fuel-efficient vehicles, indicating a potential market shift towards smaller, more efficient engines. Manufacturers might consider investing in technology to improve engine efficiency while reducing size.

Distribution of Vehicle Prices by Make (Box Plot)¶

Insight:¶

The box plot reveals that certain makes have a wider range of prices, indicating variability in luxury and budget options within those brands.

Interpretation:¶

The presence of outliers in specific makes suggests a market for high-end vehicles that could attract affluent consumers. Understanding the price distribution across makes can aid dealerships in targeting specific consumer segments.

Correlation Between Vehicle Features (Heatmap)¶

Insight:¶

The heatmap illustrates correlations among various vehicle features, such as engine size, fuel efficiency, and price.

Interpretation:¶

Strong correlations (e.g., between engine size and fuel consumption) provide valuable insights for manufacturers focusing on product development. They can prioritize features that align with consumer preferences for fuel efficiency without compromising performance.

Key Findings¶

Market Dynamics:¶

The data visualizations collectively highlight significant trends in consumer behavior, preferences for fuel efficiency, and the economic factors influencing vehicle prices.

Strategic Implications:¶

Manufacturers and dealerships can use these insights to adapt their offerings, align marketing strategies with consumer preferences, and make data-driven decisions in product development.

Opportunities for Growth:¶

The analysis points to potential opportunities for innovation, especially in fuel-efficient and environmentally friendly vehicles, aligning with global sustainability trends.

Justification for Dataset Choice¶

Interest¶

Choose a dataset that resonates with your interests, whether related to business, management, finance, health, or another domain.

if you are interested in e-commerce, you might choose a dataset that tracks online sales performance or customer reviews across different platforms.

Relevance¶

Clearly establish the relevance of the dataset to a broader field like business, management, or economics.

An e-commerce dataset is relevant to business as it provides insights into consumer behavior, product popularity, and the impact of marketing strategies.

A financial dataset tracking stock market trends relates to economics, business planning, and risk management.

A dataset focused on employee performance and satisfaction could relate to HR management and organizational productivity.

Context¶

Provide background information about the dataset’s origin. Was it published by a research institution, governmental organization, or business? Include details like:

The time frame covered by the data (e.g., sales data from 2019-2023).

The method of data collection (e.g., surveys, website scraping, real-time financial reports).

Whether it has been widely cited or used in research or business cases.

Define the key questions or hypotheses you want to explore through this dataset.
